Track the removed comment in context so you can restore it if the delete actor rejects.

```typescript
import { setup, assign, fromPromise } from 'xstate';

type C = { id: string; body: string };

export const thread = setup({
  types: {
    context: {} as { comments: C[]; removed: C | null },
    events: {} as
      | { type: 'LOAD'; items: C[] }
      | { type: 'DELETE'; id: string },
  },
  actors: {
    loader: fromPromise<C[], void>(async () => {
      const r = await fetch('/comments');
      return r.json();
    }),
    del: fromPromise<void, { id: string }>(async ({ input }) => {
      const r = await fetch(`/comments/${input.id}`, { method: 'DELETE' });
      if (!r.ok) throw new Error('delete failed');
    }),
  },
}).createMachine({
  id: 't',
  initial: 'idle',
  context: { comments: [], removed: null },
  states: {
    idle: {
      on: {
        LOAD: { actions: assign({ comments: ({ event }) => event.items }) },
        DELETE: {
          target: 'deleting',
          actions: assign({
            removed: ({ context, event }) =>
              context.comments.find((c) => c.id === event.id) ?? null,
            comments: ({ context, event }) =>
              context.comments.filter((c) => c.id !== event.id),
          }),
        },
      },
    },
    deleting: {
      invoke: {
        src: 'del',
        input: ({ context }) => ({ id: context.removed?.id ?? '' }),
        onDone: {
          target: 'idle',
          actions: assign({ removed: () => null }),
        },
        onError: {
          target: 'idle',
          actions: assign({
            comments: ({ context }) =>
              context.removed ? [...context.comments, context.removed] : context.comments,
            removed: () => null,
          }),
        },
      },
    },
  },
});
```

The optimistic pattern inserts the new item synchronously into context, then invokes a promise actor to confirm it against the server. `onDone` swaps the temp id for the server-assigned id and marks the item confirmed; `onError` either marks the item as failed (so the UI can show a retry affordance) or removes it. All three outcomes are typed via `setup.types` so nothing escapes strict mode.

```typescript
